), digits per limb (four versus five), dorsal scale rows (101–127 versus 83–100), and the relative axilla-groin distance (63.9–69.9 versus 49.7–59.6). From 
<emphasis box="[558,690,835,860]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="232">
<taxonomicName authority="Cochran, 1927" authorityName="Cochran" authorityYear="1927" box="[558,686,835,860]" class="Lepidosauria" family="Diploglossidae" genus="Wetmorena" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="31" pageNumber="232" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Wetmorena</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
we distinguish 
<taxonomicName authority="Gray, 1852" authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1852" box="[864,961,835,861]" class="Reptilia" family="Diploglossidae" genus="Sauresia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="31" pageNumber="232" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[864,961,835,861]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="232">Sauresia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the distance between the parietal scales (0–0.431 versus 0.447–1.03).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="31.[151,1437,150,1402]" box="[199,786,906,933]" pageId="31" pageNumber="232">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,303,906,932]" pageId="31" pageNumber="232">Content.</emphasis>
One species (
<tableCitation box="[459,545,907,933]" captionStart="TABLE 3" captionStartId="14.[151,239,1291,1315]" captionTargetBox="[163,1425,1404,2011]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="TABLE 3. Classification and distribution of lizards of the family Diploglossidae (55 species). For common names we use modifying words from literature sources, in some cases modified for consistency following guidelines (Hedges et al. 2019). The IUCN Redlist threat status is indicated in parentheses (NA = not assessed)." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/06B05B8EFFD0FFF70DF10D5C0264D214" pageId="31" pageNumber="232" tableUuid="06B05B8EFFD0FFF70DF10D5C0264D214">Table 3</tableCitation>
): 
<emphasis box="[567,786,907,933]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="232">
<taxonomicName authority="Gray, 1852" authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1852" box="[567,782,907,933]" class="Reptilia" family="Diploglossidae" genus="Sauresia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="31" pageNumber="232" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="sepsoides">Sauresia sepsoides</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="31" pageNumber="232" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="31.[151,1437,150,1402]" pageId="31" pageNumber="232">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,942,968]" pageId="31" pageNumber="232">Distribution.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Gray, 1852" authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1852" box="[359,456,943,969]" class="Reptilia" family="Diploglossidae" genus="Sauresia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="31" pageNumber="232" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[359,456,943,969]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="232">Sauresia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is only known from Hispaniola but is notably absent from the driest parts of the island, including northwestern 
<collectingCountry box="[417,473,979,1005]" name="Haiti" pageId="31" pageNumber="232">Haiti</collectingCountry>
and some areas in the southern 
<collectingCountry box="[832,1064,979,1005]" name="Dominican Republic" pageId="31" pageNumber="232">Dominican Republic</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[1079,1163,979,1005]" captionStart="FIGURE 19" captionStartId="30.[151,250,1971,1995]" captionTargetBox="[202,1386,593,1946]" captionTargetId="figure-120@30.[201,1386,586,1947]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURE 19. (A) In life image of Sauresia sepsoides (Voucher not available, SBH 267756). Photograph by S. B. Hedges. (B) The distribution of Sauresia on Hispaniola and islets. Arrow indicates distribution on Grande Cayemite." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4775497" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4775497/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="232">Fig. 19</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="31" pageNumber="232" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="31.[151,1437,150,1402]" pageId="31" pageNumber="232">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1015,1041]" pageId="31" pageNumber="232">Etymology.</emphasis>
The generic name (
<taxonomicName authority="Gray, 1852" authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1852" box="[559,656,1015,1041]" class="Reptilia" family="Diploglossidae" genus="Sauresia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="31" pageNumber="232" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[559,656,1015,1041]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="232">Sauresia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) is a feminine noun derived from the Greek word 
<emphasis box="[1225,1299,1015,1040]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="232">sauros</emphasis>
(lizard) and the suffix - 
<emphasis box="[272,317,1051,1076]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="232">esia</emphasis>
(originating within), alluding to the fact that members of this genus resemble snakes but are actually lizards.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="31" pageNumber="232" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="31.[151,1437,150,1402]" pageId="31" pageNumber="232">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1123,1149]" pageId="31" pageNumber="232">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Gray, 1852" authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1852" box="[321,418,1123,1149]" class="Reptilia" family="Diploglossidae" genus="Sauresia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="31" pageNumber="232" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[321,418,1123,1149]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="232">Sauresia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a monophyletic clade that has a support value of 100% in Bayesian and ML analyses (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1748,1772]" captionTargetBox="[175,1412,181,1725]" captionTargetId="figure-17@9.[175,1412,181,1725]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 2. Phylogenetic tree of diploglossid lizards based on sequences of nine genes: four mitochondrial genes (CytB, ND2, 12S rRNA, and 16S rRNA) and five nuclear genes (AMEL, BDNF, PLPR, RAG1, and ZFP36). Maximum likelihood tree obtained from the nine-gene dataset (59 individuals; 6,949 sites).A scale bar indicates 5% sequence divergence. The numbers at nodes are ML bootstrap values, followed by Bayesian posterior probabilities; asterisks indicate significant (≥ 95%) support, and a dash or zero value indicates weak (&lt;50%) support. The tree is rooted with Pseudopus apodus (Anguidae)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4775446" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4775446/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="232">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
). For most of the time since it was named in 1852, 
<taxonomicName authority="Gray, 1852" authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1852" box="[754,851,1159,1185]" class="Reptilia" family="Diploglossidae" genus="Sauresia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="31" pageNumber="232" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[754,851,1159,1185]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="232">Sauresia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been recognized as a valid genus, distinct from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1839" box="[151,246,1195,1221]" class="Reptilia" family="Anguidae" genus="Celestus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="31" pageNumber="232" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,246,1195,1221]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="232">Celestus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The genus was synonomized with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1839" box="[642,737,1195,1221]" class="Reptilia" family="Anguidae" genus="Celestus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="31" pageNumber="232" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[642,737,1195,1221]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="232">Celestus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Hass, C. A. &amp; Maxson, L. R. &amp; Hedges, S. B." box="[777,974,1195,1221]" pageId="31" pageNumber="232" pagination="15 - 33" refId="ref22877" refString="Hass, C. A., Maxson, L. R. &amp; Hedges, S. B. (2001) Relationships and divergence times of West Indian amphibians and reptiles: Insights from albumin immunology. In: Woods, C. A. &amp; Sergile, F. E. (Eds.), Biogeography of the West Indies: Patterns and Perspectives. 2 nd Edition. CRC Press, Boca Raton, Florida, pp. 15 - 33. https: // doi. org / 10.1201 / 9781420039481 - 11" type="book chapter" year="2001">
Hass 
<emphasis box="[838,893,1195,1221]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="232">et al.</emphasis>
(2001)
</bibRefCitation>
because their study using immunological data found relationships that differed from previous studies (
<bibRefCitation author="Savage, J. M. &amp; Lips, K. R." box="[836,1073,1231,1257]" pageId="31" pageNumber="232" pagination="817 - 842" refId="ref24772" refString="Savage, J. M. &amp; Lips, K. R. (1993) A review of the status and biogeography of the lizard genera Celestus and Diploglossus (Squamata: Anguidae), with description of two new species from Costa Rica. Revista de Biologia Tropical, 41, 817 - 842." type="journal article" year="1993">Savage &amp; Lips 1993</bibRefCitation>
). Our study shows that the stem divergence time of 
<taxonomicName authority="Gray, 1852" authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1852" box="[367,464,1267,1293]" class="Reptilia" family="Diploglossidae" genus="Sauresia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="31" pageNumber="232" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[367,464,1267,1293]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="232">Sauresia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is comparable to the stem times of other genera of celestines (
<figureCitation box="[1161,1229,1267,1293]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1680,1704]" captionTargetBox="[152,1436,181,1655]" captionTargetId="figure-26@10.[152,1436,181,1656]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 3. Timetree of Diploglossidae based on sequences of nine genes: four mitochondrial genes (CytB, ND2, 12S rRNA, and 16S rRNA) and five nuclear genes (AMEL, BDNF, PLPR, RAG1, and ZFP36). Nodes show divergence times in millions of years. A scale bar indicates time (6 million years ago, Mya). We show Bayesian credibility ranges as gray bars at nodes." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4775450" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4775450/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="232">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
). Our phylogenies also show high levels of divergence (4–7 Mya) among populations of this species (
<figureCitation box="[1091,1160,1303,1329]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1680,1704]" captionTargetBox="[152,1436,181,1655]" captionTargetId="figure-26@10.[152,1436,181,1656]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 3. Timetree of Diploglossidae based on sequences of nine genes: four mitochondrial genes (CytB, ND2, 12S rRNA, and 16S rRNA) and five nuclear genes (AMEL, BDNF, PLPR, RAG1, and ZFP36). Nodes show divergence times in millions of years. A scale bar indicates time (6 million years ago, Mya). We show Bayesian credibility ranges as gray bars at nodes." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4775450" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4775450/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="232">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
). These results, together with other molecular and morphological data, and greater sampling of populations, indicate that the genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Gray, 1852" authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1852" box="[1339,1436,1339,1365]" class="Reptilia" family="Diploglossidae" genus="Sauresia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="31" pageNumber="232" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1339,1436,1339,1365]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="232">Sauresia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
includes at least 11 additional species (Schools &amp; Hedges, unpubl.).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
